Located within the City of Mountain View, the study area for this project is the North Bayshore Change
Area as defined in the 2030 City of Mountain View General Plan and which will be further studied in
the North Bayshore Precise Plan update. The study area is bounded by Shoreline Park and the San
Francisco Bay to the north, Adobe Creek and the Palo Alto Baylands Park to the west, and Stevens
Creek to the east. Highway 101 bounds the southern and western sides of the study area.
It is important to note that the study efforts will extend beyond the boundaries of the North Bayshore
Change Area in order to help define and improve the existing and future transportation connections
between North Bayshore and the core economic and employment centers in Mountain View, including
the Mountain View Transportation Center in Downtown and the NASA Ames research area.
Stakeholder outreach for the project has included meetings with several Shoreline area employers and
interest groups, Caltrain platform and shuttle surveys as well as one stakeholder workshop.

The majority of travel demand within the Shoreline study area is generated from employment‐based
trips. The four major employers within the study area are Google, Intuit, Microsoft, and LinkedIn.
Currently these employers utilize transportation demand management (TDM) measures to encourage
alternative travel modes, recognizing the inherent difficulty of accessing the area via single‐occupancy
vehicles (SOV) due to the geographical constraints of the Shoreline area which limit traffic capacity
and access to the regional transit network. In addition, some employers are actively seeking to reduce
emissions by increasing their employees’ alternative mode access. Table E‐3 summarizes the current
TDM measures employed by Google, Microsoft, LinkedIn, and Intuit.
Based on interviews with major employers in the area, the success of non‐SOV travel options tends to
be correlated with the distance an employee lives from the workplace. According to both Google and
Intuit, there was high regional transit and shuttle use for employees who live more than 10 miles from
the office, due to the provisions of TDM measures that allow peak period commute trips to and from
work to be reasonable alternatives to driving to the study area. However, employees who live less
than 10 miles away tend to be more reluctant to choose alternative modes when commuting to the
Shoreline area, as their commute by automobile is reasonably convenient when compared to the
availability of high quality local transit service and bicycle/pedestrian infrastructure.

The Shoreline area has a developed but somewhat incomplete bicycle and pedestrian network.
Despite the amount of existing bicycle infrastructure in the study area, gaps exist between origins and

primarily geared towards the “confident and enthusiastic” bicyclist and has elements that may be
daunting to “interested but concerned” bicyclists. Infrastructure includes several Class I bicycle‐only
paths and Class II striped bicycle lanes traversing in and through the study area.

connectivity and accessibility. Furthermore, roadway infrastructure segregates different travel
modes, resulting in conflict points where high pedestrian and bicycle demand coincide with high
vehicular demand, such as at some roadway intersections near the Google campus.

The Shoreline study area is not served by a comprehensive integrated transit service; rather, it is
served by multiple transit services in an ad hoc manner. The patchwork of transit service between
public and private transit is a direct result of the sizable increase in employment in the past decade,
insufficient transit planning to accommodate this employment increase, and the resultant lack of
frequent and accessible local public transit service into the study area. Overall, this results in a transit
system where private employers essentially replace local public transit with their own private
shuttles to allow employees to reach their campuses, as public transit in itself does not provide
sufficient options for commuters or the general public.
The two main regional transit services are Caltrain and regional employer‐provided shuttles. Google is
the only employer that provides a comprehensive shuttle program, often via a point‐to‐point direct
shuttle service directly to their Shoreline campus. This type of service is particularly successful as it
offers employees amenities such as Wi‐Fi, time savings, and direct access from home to the Google
campus, whereas typical transit services would have to make scheduled stops on a planned route and
connect through transit hubs such as the Mountain View Caltrain Station. Other employers are
currently unable to fund/provide this level of service. As such, only a small segment of the Shoreline
employment population has the high level of transit connectivity that is provided to Google
employees. Other local services include last‐mile shuttle links from Caltrain and ACE to the study area,
VTA light rail from downtown Mountain View to NASA Ames, and local VTA bus service. However, the
Shoreline Area can appear isolated and as a result present some considerable gaps for employees
trying to reach the area by transit alone.
Light Rail Transit: VTA Light Rail Transit (LRT) 902 line provides service from the Downtown
Mountain View Caltrain Station to the NASA Ames Station, but the closest stop is still located more
than two (2) miles from the study area.
VTA Bus: Two VTA bus lines (40 and 51), one express bus (120), and one commute‐only ACE shuttle
bus line (824) serve the Shoreline area and NASA Ames/Moffett Field. However, these bus lines do not
serve the Downtown Mountain View LRT or Caltrain stations.
Local Shuttles at Caltrain Station: The local shuttles consist of a public shuttle (operated by Google)
and a number of employer shuttles providing last‐mile connectivity to their campuses. The shuttle
operator survey indicated at least five private employer shuttles connecting the Downtown Mountain
View Caltrain Station to the Shoreline area. The shuttle driver survey found at least 11 additional
shuttles serving various other employers located elsewhere from the Mountain View Caltrain Station.

LinkedIn, and Intuit. In order to analyze existing conditions related to the travel behavior of area
commuters, the employers were asked to provide overall employee information (e.g., number of
employees, origin zip codes, mode split), information related to shuttle services to their campus (e.g.,

The major employers in the Shoreline study area have instituted a wide range of transportation
demand management (TDM) measures to reduce the number of single‐occupancy vehicle trips within
the study area and to significantly reduce emissions created by their employees’ daily commutes.

light rail or Caltrain can use the Shoreline or Mary Moffett Caltrain Shuttles to get to the Google
campus. In addition to helping fund the Shoreline Caltrain Shuttle, Google also offers free shuttles to
several San Francisco, Peninsula, East Bay, South Bay, and Santa Cruz locations and a local shuttle
service to Sunnyvale and Mountain View. Google has designed these shuttles to be an extension of the
work environment and has provided workstations and a wireless internet connection on these
The routes and stops for the regional shuttles are located near current transit stations, which allows

agreement with the Alameda‐Contra Costa Transit District (AC Transit) and Bay Area Rapid Transit

The North Bayshore study area has a developed bicycle network. There are bike lanes on two of the
three overcrossings accessing the study area, as well as bike lanes on sections of Bayshore Parkway,
Garcia Avenue, Charleston Road, Amphitheatre Parkway, Rengstorff Avenue, and Shoreline Boulevard.
There are also two multi‐use trails providing vehicle‐separated access to the study area for bicyclists
and pedestrians, one of which (Permanente Creek) connects directly to the bike lanes within the study
However, despite the amount of existing bicycle infrastructure in the study area however, significant
gaps still exist between origins and destinations, both within and without the study area. Additionally,
the current bicycle infrastructure is primarily geared towards the “confident and enthusiastic”
bicyclist and has elements that are daunting to “interested but concerned” bicyclists.
The pedestrian sidewalk network in the North Bayshore study area varies significantly. As technology
companies redevelop their properties, sidewalks were often enhanced to the standards in vogue at the
time of construction. This leaves varying sidewalk (and street) typologies depending upon the year
when the adjacent properties were developed. The northwestern area of North Bayshore, one of the
oldest areas, has narrow attached sidewalks that are sometimes incomplete. In the central area of
North Bayshore, sidewalks are often detached from the street. These sidewalks tend to meander
through trees and bushes, sometimes elevated from the street by a landscaped berm. The Shoreline
Boulevard overcrossing, having been recently rebuilt, has wide curb‐attached sidewalks. See Figures
Due to the development pattern of many tech campuses over the last few decades, most of the
buildings in the North Bayshore study area are removed from the street, with large amounts of surface
parking between the street (and sidewalk) and the destinations of pedestrians. The combination of
setback buildings and prohibited on‐street parking provides very little utility and activity on many
sidewalks in the plan area. Many sidewalks within the plan area are the sole domain of the pleasure‐
stroll due to the impracticality of walking for any other purpose.

transportation connections for pedestrian and bicyclist transportation in the area. Appendix C
provides a detailed Opportunities and Constraints Analysis for Pedestrian and Bike Facilities and
Appendix D provides detailed information describing additional roadways of interest for the study
The Bay Trail runs through Shoreline Park to the north of the study area. The Trail connects with both
the Permanente Creek Trail and the Stevens Creek Trail. There are trailheads for the Bay Trail in the
study area at Terminal Boulevard at San Antonio Road, at Terminal Boulevard at Broderick Way, and
where Shoreline Boulevard leaves the study area. The Bay Trail extends to the west through Palo Alto
and East Palo Alto, and to the east through Sunnyvale and Santa Clara.
